{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17532997","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17532997"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:31:57+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:31:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14734"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14734","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14734"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.15,0.71,0.01,0.11]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7427"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108045"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7427","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7427"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14734"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90458"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"10962"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18132"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35644"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40267"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108045","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/108045"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic for review following percutaneous coronary intervention (PCI) six months ago. He underwent uncomplicated PCI with a drug-eluting stent to his right coronary artery for acute coronary syndrome. The revascularisation procedure was straightforward with no complications. An echocardiogram done at that time showed preserved left ventricular ejection fraction. He has had no recurrent ischaemic events since the procedure. He has a medical history of hypertension and hypercholesterolaemia. His medications include aspirin, ticagrelor, atorvastatin, and perindopril. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate duration of dual antiplatelet therapy?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["One month","Three months","12 months","24 months","Lifelong"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has undergone uncomplicated PCI with a drug-eluting stent for acute coronary syndrome. The duration of dual antiplatelet therapy (DAPT) depends on several factors, including the clinical presentation, the type of stent used, and the patient\u0027s bleeding and ischaemic risk.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E12 months\u003C/strong\u003E of DAPT is the current standard recommendation for most patients who undergo PCI with contemporary drug-eluting stents for acute coronary syndrome. This patient underwent an uncomplicated procedure and experienced no recurrent ischaemic events at the six-month follow-up, making 12 months the appropriate duration. After this period, patients should continue single antiplatelet therapy indefinitely, usually with aspirin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOne to three months\u003C/strong\u003E of DAPT may be considered in patients at high bleeding risk. Otherwise, it is generally too short for patients who undergo PCI with contemporary drug-eluting stents for acute coronary syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELong-term \u003Cstrong\u003E(\u0026gt;12 months)\u003C/strong\u003E DAPT may be considered in selected patients with recurrent ischaemic events on DAPT, or who are at high risk for them (e.g., left main or anterior descending artery disease, complex PCI). Neither of these features is seen in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EContemporary guidelines emphasise individualised decision-making regarding DAPT duration, balancing ischaemic and bleeding risks.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The standard duration of dual antiplatelet therapy after uncomplicated PCI with a drug-eluting stent for acute coronary syndrome is 6-12 months.","DAPT duration may be shortened in patients at high bleeding risk or extended in those at high risk of recurrent ischaemic events.","After completing DAPT, patients should continue single antiplatelet therapy indefinitely."],"references":["Brieger D, Cullen L, Briffa T, Zaman S, Scott I, Papendick C, Bardsley K, Baumann A, Bennett AS, Clark RA, Edelman JJ, Inglis SC, Kuhn L, Livori A, Redfern J, Schneider H, Stewart J, Thomas L, Wing-Lun E, Zhang L, Ho E, Matthews S; other members of the Heart Foundation Working Group. Electronic address: clinicalevidence@heartfoundation.org.au. National Heart Foundation of Australia \u0026 Cardiac Society of Australia and New Zealand: Comprehensive Australian Clinical Guideline for Diagnosing and Managing Acute Coronary Syndromes 2025. Heart Lung Circ. 2025 Apr;34(4):309-397. doi: 10.1016/j.hlc.2025.02.102. PMID: 40180468. Available from: https://www.heartfoundation.org.au/for-professionals/acs-guideline?tab=0"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90458"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14734"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90458","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/90458"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-05T20:51:40+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-05T20:52:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7427"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108045"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags